section.p:
It turns out that area also works with fractions, though you do need to be a bit more careful with your drawings
to know where your integers are. Here is the representation of the product \frac{2}{3} \cdot \frac{5}{4}
as an area.

image.latex-image:
\begin{tikzpicture} [scale=2]
	\draw[fill=lightgray] (0,0) rectangle (1.25,0.667); 
	\draw[ultra thick] (0,0) rectangle (2,1); 
	\draw[ultra thick] (0,0) grid (2,1); 
	\draw (0,0.333) -- ++ (2,0); 
	\draw (0,0.667) -- ++ (2,0); 
	\draw (0.25,0) -- ++ (0,1); 
	\draw (0.5,0) -- ++ (0,1); 
	\draw (0.75,0) -- ++ (0,1); 
	\draw (1.25,0) -- ++ (0,1); 
	\draw (1.5,0) -- ++ (0,1); 
	\draw (1.75,0) -- ++ (0,1); 
	\draw (0,0) node[anchor=north] {$0$}; 
	\draw (1,0) node[anchor=north] {$1$}; 
	\draw (2,0) node[anchor=north] {$2$}; 
	\draw (1.25,0) node[anchor=north] {$\frac{5}{4}$}; 
	\draw (0,0) node[anchor=east] {$0$}; 
	\draw (0,1) node[anchor=east] {$1$}; 
	\draw (0,0.667) node[anchor=east] {$\frac{2}{3}$}; 
\end{tikzpicture}
